body:
The entire problem is outlined here https://users.rust-lang.org/t/confusion-about-module-name-ambiguity/50512 w/o having found a satisfying solution. 

The core of the problem has been summarized by a user in the thread, so I quote that here:

Project is `cargo new lib-test``

# This works

```
// src/main.rs
mod lib;
fn main {}
```
```
// src/lib.rs
```

# This doesn't compile

```
// src/main.rs
mod lib;
fn main {}
```

```
// src/lib.rs
mod test;
```

```
// src/test.rs
```

The error suggests help: to create the module `test`, create file "src/lib/test.rs". Doing this gives the reverse suggestion: create src/test.rs

The thread suggests to remove `mod lib;` from `main.rs` and call the mod test functions provided by `lib.rs`:

```
// src/test.rs
pub fn test()  {
}
```

```
// src/lib.rs
pub mod test;

pub fn test() {}
```

```
use lib_test::test::test;

fn main() {
    test();
}

```

`lib.rs` needs to be altered so, that `pub mod test;` is exported.

This works, compiles w/o warning and runs. It just makes VSCode to give an error notation in `lib.rs`:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/731020/96973687-86ce5680-1518-11eb-89d8-c815df4c840d.png)

So the question is: Is the suggested solution the "right" solution to do this task? Calling functions from one and the same modules in a lib _and_ a bin?
